Reduce the skewness of Income, CCAvg and Mortgage columns¶
In [34]:
# Income - We can apply the sqrt transformation to Income column and reduce skewness in the data
# Create another column containing the sqrt of Income column and whose distribution is more normal
loan_df['SQRT_Income'] = np.sqrt(loan_df['Income'])

# Plot and compare the skewness before and after the transformation
plt.figure(1, figsize=(16,10))
plt.subplot(231)
sns.distplot(loan_df['Income'])
plt.axvline(loan_df['Income'].mean(), color='k', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
plt.subplot(232)
sns.distplot(loan_df['SQRT_Income'])
plt.axvline(loan_df['SQRT_Income'].mean(), color='k', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)

# Get the skewness value before and after the transformation
print('Skew of Income data:', loan_df['Income'].skew())
print('Skew of transformed Income data:', loan_df['SQRT_Income'].skew())

# Right skew in Income data has been reduced. Distribution is more normal. 

Skew of Income data: 0.8413386072610816
Skew of transformed Income data: 0.26043573246879353
In [35]:
# CCAvg - We can apply the sqrt transformation to CCAvg column and reduce skewness in the data
# Create another column containing the sqrt of CCAvg column and whose distribution is more normal
loan_df['SQRT_CCAvg'] = np.sqrt(loan_df['CCAvg'])

# Plot and compare the skewness before and after the transformation
plt.figure(1, figsize=(16,10))
plt.subplot(231)
sns.distplot(loan_df['CCAvg'])
plt.axvline(loan_df['CCAvg'].mean(), color='k', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
plt.subplot(232)
sns.distplot(loan_df['SQRT_CCAvg'])
plt.axvline(loan_df['SQRT_CCAvg'].mean(), color='k', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)

# Get the skewness value before and after the transformation
print('Skew of CCAvg data:', loan_df['CCAvg'].skew())

Logistic Regression¶
In [39]:
# Prepare data for logistic regression
# 1. Binary logistic regression requires the dependent variable to be binary and ordinal.
# The target variable, 'Personal Loan', has only two outcomes which are ordinal, 1 for Offer Accepted, and 0 for Offer Rejected

# 2. It requires the observations to be independent of each other.
# Since the ids are all unique, we can say that the obs are independent of each other

# 3. It requires there to be little or no multicollinearity among the independent variables.
# The Age & Experience features have very high correlation between them. Will drop the Experience feature.
lr_loan_df = loan_df
lr_loan_df.drop(columns=['Experience'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# 4. It assumes linearity of independent variables and log odds.

# 5. It requires large sample sizes
# Sample size is 5000, which is sufficient considering the number of features present in the data

In [49]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score
from sklearn.metrics import auc
from sklearn.metrics import average_precision_score
In [91]:
def print_pr_auc(model, X_test, y_test, y_pred):
    # Predict probabilities
    probs = model.predict_proba(X_test)
    probs = probs[:, 1]
    
    # Calculate precision-recall curve
    precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, probs)

    # Calculate F1 score
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)

    # Calculate precision-recall AUC
    auc_score = auc(recall, precision)

    # Calculate average precision score
    ap = average_precision_score(y_test, probs)
    print('f1=%.3f auc=%.3f ap=%.3f' % (f1, auc_score, ap))

    # Plot no skill
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0.5, 0.5], linestyle='--')

    # Plot the precision-recall curve for the model
    plt.plot(recall, precision, marker='.')

# Gaussian Naive Bayes Classifier makes the assumptions that:
# The continuous predictor features are assumed to be distributed according to a Gaussian/Normal distribution
    # Verified that all continuous features are either already normal or transformed to normal using Sqrt/log transformations
# The predictor features are independent of each other
    # Age and Experience had high correlation. Hence dropped Experience column earlier.
    # CCAvg/Income and CD Account/Securities Account columns have high correlation too. Will check the performance of the classifier with and without these pairs.
# The predictors have an equal effect on the outcome
    # The predictor variables have varying correlation with the target variable. Income followed by CCAvg and CD Account have the highest correlation. 
    # The Gaussian Naive Bayes theorem works well even without some of the assumptions addressed.

# Cross Validation
# creating odd list of K for KNN
myList = list(range(1,20))

# subsetting just the odd ones
neighbors = list(filter(lambda x: x % 2 != 0, myList))
In [97]:
# empty list that will hold accuracy scores
ac_scores = []

# perform accuracy metrics for values from 1,3,5....19
for k in neighbors:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # predict the response
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    # evaluate accuracy
    scores = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    ac_scores.append(scores)

# changing to misclassification error
MSE = [1 - x for x in ac_scores]

# determining best k
optimal_k = neighbors[MSE.index(min(MSE))]
print("The optimal number of neighbors is %d" % optimal_k)

The optimal number of neighbors is 3
